## Acceptance Criteria

### Must-have

- `sfs resume` preflights target tool rules for supported resume targets
- current canonical rules are used by default
- source session rules provenance is displayed when present
- only the target tool file is written
- missing files are written
- SessionFS-managed files are refreshed
- unmanaged files are not overwritten unless `--force-rules`
- `--no-rules-sync` skips the preflight
- partial compile used by resume never creates canonical history versions
- resume-time sync works even when the target tool is not in `enabled_tools`
- resume still succeeds if rules sync fails
- no global config files are modified

### Must-not

- do not overwrite unmanaged files silently
- do not write all tool files during resume
- do not mutate canonical `enabled_tools`
- do not default to historical session rules
- do not fail resume just because rules sync failed

---

## Not In Scope

Defer these:

- `--rules-from-session`
- `--rules-version N`
- syncing global rules files during resume
- dashboard UX for resume-time rules selection
- agent-specific rules branching during collab
- strict mode that hard-fails resume on rules-sync failure

---

## Guiding Sentence

**`sfs resume` should carry the conversation across tools and preflight the target tool's current canonical project rules, without ever silently taking ownership of a user-managed file.**
